ponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eductus venosus\u003C/strong\u003E is a vascular shunt that allows oxygenated blood from the umbilical vein to bypass the liver and flow directly into the inferior vena cava. This ensures that highly oxygenated blood from the placenta can reach the fetal heart efficiently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options describe other structures or non-existent connections. The connection between the \u003Cstrong\u003Eright atrium and left atrium\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the foramen ovale, while the connection between the \u003Cstrong\u003Epulmonary artery and aorta\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the ductus arteriosus. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eportal vein to hepatic vein\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior vena cava to pulmonary vein\u003C/strong\u003E connections do not exist in fetal circulation. The ductus venosus closes shortly after birth when placental circulation ceases, becoming the ligamentum venosum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The ductus venosus carries oxygenated blood from the umbilical vein directly to the inferior vena cava in the developing fetus.","The ductus venosus functionally closes within hours of birth and anatomically closes within 2-3 weeks."],"references":["Sidhu PS, Lui F. Embryology, Ductus Venosus. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK547759/#"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95924"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15951"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95924"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T11:59:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T11:59:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8642"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113905"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":